      {
        "title": "Paragraph Elements and Inline Semantics in a Real Article",
        "description": "This example shows the p element used correctly alongside all major inline text elements in context. Every inline element is chosen for its semantic meaning, not its visual output. The example also demonstrates the difference between strong and b, and between em and i, which are the most commonly confused pairs.",
        "code_snippet": "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n  <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n  <title>Inline Text Semantics Demo</title>\n  <style>\n    body { font-family: Georgia, serif; max-width: 680px;\n           margin: 2rem auto; padding: 0 1rem; line-height: 1.8; }\n    h1   { font-size: 1.6rem; }\n    h2   { font-size: 1.2rem; margin-top: 2rem; }\n    abbr { cursor: help; }\n    kbd  { background: #f1f5f9; border: 1px solid #cbd5e1;\n           border-radius: 4px; padding: 0.1rem 0.4rem;\n           font-size: 0.85em; }\n    code { background: #f1f5f9; border-radius: 3px;\n           padding: 0.1rem 0.35rem; font-size: 0.88em; }\n    mark { background: #fef08a; border-radius: 2px; padding: 0 0.15rem; }\n    time { font-style: normal; }\n  </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n  <h1>Understanding CSS Specificity</h1>\n\n  <!--\n    Plain paragraph: the default use case.\n    Each <p> gets automatic top and bottom margin from the browser stylesheet.\n    Never add <br><br> between paragraphs to simulate spacing.\n    Use CSS margin-bottom on p instead.\n  -->\n  <p>\n    CSS specificity is the algorithm browsers use to decide which style rule\n    wins when multiple rules target the same element. Every selector has a\n    score, and the rule with the highest score takes effect.\n  </p>\n\n\n  <h2>strong vs b</h2>\n  <!--\n    strong: semantic importance. Screen readers may change tone.\n    b: stylistically bold but carries no extra importance or urgency.\n  -->\n  <p>\n    When two rules conflict, the one with higher specificity wins.\n    <strong>Inline styles always win over class and element selectors.</strong>\n    This is why inline styles should be avoided in production code.\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The main libraries covered in this guide are\n    <b>Tailwind CSS</b>, <b>Bootstrap</b>, and <b>Bulma</b>.\n    <!-- b is correct here: product names styled bold, no urgency implied -->\n  </p>\n\n\n  <h2>em vs i</h2>\n  <!--\n    em: stress emphasis that shifts meaning, like spoken inflection.\n    i: italic for non-emphasis reasons: foreign words, technical terms, titles.\n  -->\n  <p>\n    You should use the selector with the <em>highest</em> specificity,\n    not simply the one that appears <em>last</em> in the stylesheet.\n    <!-- em: stressing these specific words changes the meaning of the sentence -->\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The property is known as <i>specificity</i> in the\n    <cite>CSS Cascading and Inheritance specification</cite>.\n    <!-- i: technical term; cite: title of a specification document -->\n  </p>\n\n\n  <h2>mark, del, ins</h2>\n  <p>\n    Browser support for the <mark>:has() pseudo-class</mark> has improved\n    significantly since 2023.\n    <!-- mark: highlighted term relevant to a search or annotation context -->\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The old specificity formula was <del>0-0-0-1</del>\n    and is now expressed as <ins>0-0-1</ins> in the updated specification.\n    <!-- del: removed content; ins: inserted replacement content -->\n  </p>\n\n\n  <h2>code, kbd, abbr, sub, sup</h2>\n  <p>\n    The <code>:nth-child()</code> pseudo-class accepts\n    <abbr title=\"Argument notation for pattern matching\">An+B</abbr> syntax.\n    Press <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Shift</kbd>+<kbd>C</kbd> to open\n    <abbr title=\"Developer Tools\">DevTools</abbr> and inspect specificity scores.\n    <!-- code: function name; abbr: abbreviation with tooltip; kbd: keyboard keys -->\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    Specificity is calculated as a three-column score:\n    ID<sup>[1]</sup>, class<sup>[2]</sup>, element<sup>[3]</sup>.\n    Water is H<sub>2</sub>O and not related, but shows subscript usage.\n    <!-- sup: footnote markers and exponents; sub: chemical subscripts -->\n  </p>\n\n\n  <h2>q, time, small, br</h2>\n  <p>\n    As the specification states:\n    <q>specificity is determined by the selector structure, not by document order.</q>\n    <!-- q: inline quotation, browser adds the quotation marks automatically -->\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The specification was last updated on\n    <time datetime=\"2024-01-15\">15 January 2024</time>.\n    <!-- time: machine-readable date, datetime attribute is the parseable value -->\n  </p>\n  <p>\n    <small>All examples in this guide target CSS Level 4 specification.\n    Browser support may vary. Always check compatibility tables.</small>\n    <!-- small: fine print, side comments, disclaimers -->\n  </p>\n\n  <!--\n    br: use only when the line break itself is part of the content meaning.\n    Correct uses: postal addresses, poetry, song lyrics.\n    Wrong use: adding br br between paragraphs to create spacing.\n  -->\n  <p>\n    Anthropic, Inc.<br>\n    548 Market Street<br>\n    San Francisco, CA 94104\n  </p>\n\n</body>\n</html>",
        "output": "Page renders a CSS Specificity article with all inline elements displayed in context. strong appears bold with semantic weight for the inline styles warning. b appears bold for library names without urgency. em italicises stressed words that shift sentence meaning. i italicises the technical term and cite italicises the specification title. mark highlights the :has() term in yellow. del shows the old formula struck through and ins shows the new formula underlined. code renders in monospace, kbd shows keyboard keys with borders, abbr shows dotted underlines with tooltips. sup renders footnote markers raised. The address block uses br for meaningful line breaks.",
