      {
        "title": "Common Paragraph Mistakes: Spacing, Nesting, and Misused Elements",
        "description": "This example contrasts the wrong and right way to handle three common paragraph mistakes: using br for spacing instead of CSS, nesting block elements inside p, and using visual elements like b and i where semantic elements like strong and em belong. Understanding these prevents a category of subtle rendering and accessibility bugs.",
        "code_snippet": "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n  <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n  <title>Paragraph Mistakes</title>\n  <style>\n    body { font-family: sans-serif; max-width: 680px; margin: 2rem auto; padding: 0 1rem; }\n    h2   { font-size: 1rem; margin-top: 1.75rem; color: #1e293b; }\n    .wrong { border-left: 3px solid #dc2626; padding-left: 1rem; background: #fef2f2;\n             border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0; padding: 0.75rem 1rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }\n    .right { border-left: 3px solid #16a34a; padding-left: 1rem; background: #f0fdf4;\n             border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0; padding: 0.75rem 1rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }\n    .label { font-size: 0.7rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase;\n             letter-spacing: 0.05em; margin-bottom: 0.4rem; }\n    .wrong .label { color: #dc2626; }\n    .right .label { color: #16a34a; }\n\n    /* RIGHT: use CSS for paragraph spacing, never br br -->\n    p.spaced { margin-bottom: 1.25rem; }\n  </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n  <h1>Common Paragraph Mistakes</h1>\n\n\n  <!-- MISTAKE 1: using br br for spacing between paragraphs -->\n  <h2>1. Paragraph Spacing</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"wrong\">\n    <p class=\"label\">Wrong: br br for spacing</p>\n    First paragraph of text.<br><br>\n    Second paragraph of text.<br><br>\n    Third paragraph of text.\n    <!--\n      Problems:\n      - Not real paragraphs, so screen readers cannot navigate between them\n      - No semantic structure, search engines see one block of text\n      - Spacing cannot be changed by CSS targeting p elements\n    -->\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"right\">\n    <p class=\"label\">Right: real p elements with CSS margin</p>\n    <p class=\"spaced\">First paragraph of text.</p>\n    <p class=\"spaced\">Second paragraph of text.</p>\n    <p>Third paragraph of text.</p>\n    <!--\n      Benefits:\n      - Screen readers announce each paragraph boundary\n      - Spacing is controlled centrally via CSS\n      - Structure is semantically correct\n    -->\n  </div>\n\n\n  <!-- MISTAKE 2: nesting block elements inside p -->\n  <h2>2. Invalid Nesting</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"wrong\">\n    <p class=\"label\">Wrong: block elements inside p</p>\n    <!--\n      p cannot contain block-level elements.\n      When a browser sees <div> inside <p>, it auto-closes the <p>\n      before the <div>, then opens a new implicit <p> after.\n      The rendered output is unpredictable.\n    -->\n    <!-- <p>Introduction text <div>Block content</div> more text</p> -->\n    <!-- <p>Text <ul><li>Item</li></ul></p>                          -->\n    <!-- <p>Text <h2>Subheading</h2></p>                            -->\n    <p style=\"color:#dc2626;font-style:italic;\">\n      p cannot contain div, ul, ol, h1-h6, blockquote, or table.\n      Attempting this causes the browser to auto-close the p early.\n    </p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"right\">\n    <p class=\"label\">Right: p contains only inline content</p>\n    <p>Introduction text with <strong>inline emphasis</strong> and\n       <a href=\"/docs\">inline links</a>.</p>\n    <!--\n      p can contain:\n      text nodes, a, span, strong, em, b, i, code, abbr, mark,\n      small, del, ins, sub, sup, time, br, img, input, label\n      (any phrasing content element)\n    -->\n  </div>\n\n\n  <!-- MISTAKE 3: visual elements where semantic elements belong -->\n  <h2>3. Visual vs Semantic Elements</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"wrong\">\n    <p class=\"label\">Wrong: visual styling without meaning</p>\n    <p>\n      <b>Warning:</b> This action cannot be undone.\n      <!-- b: bold but no importance signal. Screen readers do not change tone. -->\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      Do <i>not</i> click Submit twice.\n      <!-- i: italic but no stress. Meaning is not emphasised for screen readers. -->\n    </p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"right\">\n    <p class=\"label\">Right: semantic elements that communicate meaning</p>\n    <p>\n      <strong>Warning:</strong> This action cannot be undone.\n      <!-- strong: screen readers announce importance; search engines weight it -->\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      Do <em>not</em> click Submit twice.\n      <!-- em: stress emphasis; screen readers may inflect the word differently -->\n    </p>\n  </div>\n\n</body>\n</html>",
        "output": "Page renders three mistake-and-fix pairs. The spacing section shows the wrong version as a single block of text with visible line gaps from br, and the right version as three clearly separated p elements. The nesting section shows an explanatory note about what block elements cannot go inside p. The semantic section shows the wrong b and i usage beside the correct strong and em usage, visually identical but semantically distinct.",
